till necessary, as javax.naming is in the JDK. \\\\n\\\\nThere are potential issues around resource registration, builtins, and how file reading is managed. I need to ensure that default application properties are handled correctly, especially when they're immutable.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Identifying Provider Issues**\\\\n\\\\nI'm noticing a potential problem after app properties become non-empty. Specifically, `this.providers.add(0, applicationPropertiesRegistrationFeature);` adds an anonymous inner class from the library. Later on, providerFactory might use reflection on this anonymous feature, which is an existing library class—probably not my concern. I'm questioning if this requires metadata and whether the class is dynamically generated.\\\\n\\\\nIt seems that the provider loading could create dynamic access in a native setting, and I wonder if we really need this feature when simply setting a property to disable service loading ends up adding a feature provider. To prevent that, I might need to override getProperties to return a map indicating false. But, if properties are empty, isEnabled returns true, potentially complicating things.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Considering Anonymous Feature Registration**\\\\n\\\\nRegistering the anonymous app properties feature might lead to unintended side effects. It could be more effective to override getProperties to return Map.of(\\\\\\\"jakarta.ws.rs.loadServices\\\\\\\", \\\\\\\"false,\\\\\\\" which does a similar job. If there are no built-in features, the Feature provider instance might not even get configured. \\\\n\\\\nWhen providerFactory registers the provider instance, it probably configures it right away, calling configure with the featureContext and setting the property as needed. I think this approach looks fine overall!\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Assessing JNDI Issues in Native Image**\\\\n\\\\nI'm considering whether the issue with the JNDI InitialContext failure in Native Image is due to unsupported javax.naming features. It seems like that might be necessary to avoid adding JNDI if it's fundamental. However, line 588 is essential. Maybe I could privately call registerJndiComponentResource. If the JNDI constructor fails, it could cause subsequent tests to fail too. I wonder if splitting line 588 into a separate test would help, but that feels unnecessary.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Exploring Dynamic Call Site Issues**\\\\n\\\\nI'm looking into potential issues with dynamic call sites in registerResources at line 488, which only happens if useScanning is true. Since our app doesn't have classes or singletons, the processApplication properties aren't registered as true. I wonder if `Application.getClasses()` might return an empty set instead of null, indicating no registration. The same potential issue might apply to `Application.getSingletons()`. Plus, `ConfiguredApplication.getProperties()` may override and return an empty map in the API.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"text\", \"text\": \"Implemented targeted coverage for `org.jboss.resteasy.core.ResteasyDeploymentImpl`.\\n\\nChanges:\\n- Added `tests/src/org.jboss.resteasy/resteasy-core/6.2.15.Final/src/test/java/org_jboss_resteasy/resteasy_core/ResteasyDeploymentImplTest.java`\\n  - Exercises string-based deployment configuration paths for:\\n    - injector factory class loading and instantiation\\n    - application class loading\\n    - constructed default context object loading/creation\\n    - scanned/provider class registration\\n    - scanned and explicit JNDI component resource class loading\\n    - scanned resources\\n    - resource builder class loading/instantiation\\n    - builder-managed resource loading\\n    - explicit resource class loading\\n- Updated `Resteasy_coreTest` top-level class to be `public`.\\n\\nI did not compile or run tests, per instructions.\", \"textSignature\": \"{\\\"v\\\":1,\\\"id\\\":\\\"msg_073818f911defdc20169fe2e14ed90819ea94907fdbe6db8d8\\\",\\\"phase\\\":\\\"final_answer\\\"}\"}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 2409, \"output\": 1214, \"cacheRead\": 30208, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 33831, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"stop\", \"timestamp\": 1778265594766, \"responseId\": \"resp_073818f911defdc20169fe2dfc4178819e8d6de0c17468d60a\"}}\n../3312-20a114be/human-intervention-logs/org.jboss.resteasy:resteasy-core:6.2.15.Final/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-05-08T18-40-21-742918Z.log:2671:[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Assessing JNDI Context Issues**\\n\\nI'm exploring whether a JNDI InitialContext can be constructed without an environment—usually, yes, using the default context. It may throw a NoInitialContextException on lookup, but not during construction. With Native Image, I'll check if JNDI is still necessary, as javax.naming is in the JDK. \\n\\nThere are potential issues around resource registration, builtins, and how file reading is managed. I need to ensure that default application properties are handled correctly, especially when they're immutable.\\n\\n**Identifying Provider Issues**\\n\\nI'm noticing a potential problem after app properties become non-empty. Specifically, `this.providers.add(0, applicationPropertiesRegistrationFeature);` adds an anonymous inner class from the library. Later on, providerFactory might use reflection on this anonymous feature, which is an existing library class—probably not my concern. I'm questioning if this requires metadata and whether the class is dynamically generated.\\n\\nIt seems that the provider loading could create dynamic access in a native setting, and I wonder if we really need this feature when simply setting a property to disable service loading ends up adding a feature provider. To prevent that, I might need to override getProperties to return a map indicating false. But, if properties are empty, isEnabled returns true, potentially complicating things.\\n\\n**Considering Anonymous Feature Registration**\\n\\nRegistering the anonymous app properties feature might lead to unintended side effects. It could be more effective to override getProperties to return Map.of(\\\"jakarta.ws.rs.loadServices\\\", \\\"false,\\\" which does a similar job. If there are no built-in features, the Feature provider instance might not even get configured. \\n\\nWhen providerFactory registers the provider instance, it probably configures it right away, calling configure with the featureContext and setting the property as needed. I think this approach looks fine overall!\\n\\n**Assessing JNDI Issues in Native Image**\\n\\nI'm considering whether the issue with the JNDI InitialContext failure in Native Image is due to unsupported javax.naming features. It seems like that might be necessary to avoid adding JNDI if it's fundamental. However, line 588 is essential. Maybe I could privately call registerJndiComponentResource. If the JNDI constructor fails, it could cause subsequent tests to fail too. I wonder if splitting line 588 into a separate test would help, but that feels unnecessary.\\n\\n**Exploring Dynamic Call Site Issues**\\n\\nI'm looking into potential issues with dynamic call sites in registerResources at line 488, which only happens if useScanning is true. Since our app doesn't have classes or singletons, the processApplication properties aren't registered as true. I wonder if `Application.getClasses()` might return an empty set instead of null, indicating no registration. The same potential issue might apply to `Application.getSingletons()`. Plus, `ConfiguredApplication.getProperties()` may override and return an empty map in the API.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\